      "source": [
        "## 1. Problem Understanding & Task Framing\n",
        "\n",
        "**Objective:** The goal of this project is to classify text descriptions of plants and fungi into three distinct categories: `edible`, `poisonous`, and `food_poisoning`.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Data Modalities & Constraints:**\n",
        "* **Modality:** The primary feature is natural language text (concatenated names, scientific names, and descriptions).\n",
        "* **Challenge:** The dataset is highly imbalanced. We have 2,440 `edible` samples, 1,414 `poisonous` samples, but only 152 `food_poisoning` samples. This severe minority class will make recall for `food_poisoning` incredibly difficult and requires careful handling through oversampling (and, if needed, class weighting).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Modeling Plan:** We will build a progressive pipeline starting from a basic Artificial Neural Network (ANN) to establish a baseline embedding. We will then transfer these learned embeddings through increasingly complex spatial and sequential architectures (CNN, Transformer, BiLSTM, BiGRU). Finally, all architectures will be combined into a Unified Ensemble to capture both local n-gram features and global sequential context."
      ]
    },
